{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775844368284,"sessionID":"ses_287725b68ffe31vjrcaNWO7QzD","part":{"id":"prt_d788f7785001PZrlk3Dhky1gK9","messageID":"msg_d788e1eba001J7HLXSozzTny8p","sessionID":"ses_287725b68ffe31vjrcaNWO7QzD","type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_functions.write:7","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/delta-spec.md","content":"# Delta Spec: AR-004 — WorkloadManager HTTP Service Framework\n\n## Overview\n\n**AR ID:** AR-004  \n**Module:** pkg/workloadmanager  \n**Language:** Go  \n**Size:** M  \n\nEstablish the HTTP service framework for the WorkloadManager component, providing RESTful APIs for managing AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter resources, health endpoints, and integration with the Kubernetes client-go library.\n\n---\n\n## Requirements\n\n### Requirement: HTTP Server Bootstrap\n\nThe system SHALL provide a configurable HTTP server that can be started and gracefully shut down.\n\n#### Scenario: Server starts with configuration\n- **GIVEN** a valid server configuration with host, port, and handler registrations\n- **WHEN** the operator calls `server.Start()`\n- **THEN** the HTTP server SHALL bind to the configured address and begin accepting connections\n\n#### Scenario: Server shuts down gracefully\n- **GIVEN** a running HTTP server with active connections\n- **WHEN** the operator calls `server.Shutdown(ctx)` with a context timeout\n- **THEN** the server SHALL stop accepting new connections, wait for existing requests to complete (within timeout), and release resources\n\n#### Scenario: Server configuration from environment\n- **GIVEN** environment variables `WORKLOAD_MANAGER_HOST` (default \"0.0.0.0\") and `WORKLOAD_MANAGER_PORT` (default \"8080\")\n- **WHEN** the operator initializes the server configuration\n- **THEN** the configuration SHALL read from these environment variables with sensible defaults\n\n#### Scenario: Server supports TLS configuration\n- **GIVEN** TLS certificate and key files specified in configuration\n- **WHEN** the operator starts the server with TLS enabled\n- **THEN** the server SHALL serve HTTPS using the provided certificates\n\n---\n\n### Requirement: Health and Readiness Endpoints\n\nThe system SHALL expose standard Kubernetes health check endpoints for liveness and readiness probes.\n\n#### Scenario: Liveness endpoint returns healthy\n- **GIVEN** the WorkloadManager HTTP server is running\n- **WHEN** a GET request is made to `/healthz`\n- **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 200 with body `{\"status\": \"ok\"}` when the process is alive\n\n#### Scenario: Readiness endpoint reflects dependency health\n- **GIVEN** the WorkloadManager has initialized all dependencies (Kubernetes client, Redis connection)\n- **WHEN** a GET request is made to `/readyz`\n- **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 200 with body `{\"status\": \"ready\"}` when all dependencies are healthy\n\n#### Scenario: Readiness endpoint returns not ready\n- **GIVEN** the WorkloadManager has a failed dependency (e.g., Kubernetes API unreachable)\n- **WHEN** a GET request is made to `/readyz`\n- **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 503 with body `{\"status\": \"not_ready\", \"reason\": \"<failure_reason>\"}`\n\n#### Scenario: Health endpoint includes detailed checks\n- **GIVEN** the configuration enables verbose health checks\n- **WHEN** a GET request is made to `/healthz?verbose=true`\n- **THEN** the server SHALL return detailed health status for each registered health check component\n\n---\n\n### Requirement: RESTful API for AgentRuntime Resources\n\nThe system SHALL expose RESTful HTTP endpoints for CRUD operations on AgentRuntime resources.\n\n#### Scenario: List AgentRuntimes\n- **GIVEN** AgentRuntime resources exist in namespace `default`\n- **WHEN** a GET request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/agentruntimes`\n- **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 200 with a JSON list of AgentRuntime objects\n\n#### Scenario: Get single AgentRuntime\n- **GIVEN** an AgentRuntime named `test-runtime` exists in namespace `default`\n- **WHEN** a GET request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/agentruntimes/test-runtime`\n- **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 200 with the AgentRuntime JSON object\n\n#### Scenario: Get non-existent AgentRuntime returns 404\n- **GIVEN** no AgentRuntime named `non-existent` exists in namespace `default`\n- **WHEN** a GET request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/agentruntimes/non-existent`\n- **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 404 with error details\n\n#### Scenario: Create AgentRuntime\n- **GIVEN** a valid AgentRuntime JSON payload\n- **WHEN** a POST request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/agentruntimes` with the payload\n- **THEN** the server SHALL create the resource via Kubernetes API and return HTTP 201 with the created object\n\n#### Scenario: Create invalid AgentRuntime returns 400\n- **GIVEN** an invalid AgentRuntime JSON payload (missing required fields)\n- **WHEN** a POST request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/agentruntimes` with the invalid payload\n- **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 400 with validation error details\n\n#### Scenario: Update AgentRuntime\n- **GIVEN** an existing AgentRuntime named `test-runtime`\n- **WHEN** a PUT request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/agentruntimes/test-runtime` with updated spec\n- **THEN** the server SHALL update the resource and return HTTP 200 with the updated object\n\n#### Scenario: Delete AgentRuntime\n- **GIVEN** an existing AgentRuntime named `test-runtime`\n- **WHEN** a DELETE request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/agentruntimes/test-runtime`\n- **THEN** the server SHALL delete the resource and return HTTP 200 with the deleted object\n\n#### Scenario: Watch AgentRuntimes\n- **GIVEN** the server supports streaming endpoints\n- **WHEN** a GET request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/agentruntimes?watch=true`\n- **THEN** the server SHALL establish a streaming connection and emit ADDED/MODIFIED/DELETED events as resources change\n\n---\n\n### Requirement: RESTful API for CodeInterpreter Resources\n\nThe system SHALL expose RESTful HTTP endpoints for CRUD operations on CodeInterpreter resources.\n\n#### Scenario: List CodeInterpreters\n- **GIVEN** CodeInterpreter resources exist in namespace `default`\n- **WHEN** a GET request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/codeinterpreters`\n- **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 200 with a JSON list of CodeInterpreter objects\n\n#### Scenario: Get single CodeInterpreter\n- **GIVEN** a CodeInterpreter named `test-interpreter` exists in namespace `default`\n- **WHEN** a GET request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/codeinterpreters/test-interpreter`\n- **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 200 with the CodeInterpreter JSON object\n\n#### Scenario: Create CodeInterpreter\n- **GIVEN** a valid CodeInterpreter JSON payload\n- **WHEN** a POST request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/codeinterpreters` with the payload\n- **THEN** the server SHALL create the resource via Kubernetes API and return HTTP 201 with the created object\n\n#### Scenario: Update CodeInterpreter\n- **GIVEN** an existing CodeInterpreter named `test-interpreter`\n- **WHEN** a PUT request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/codeinterpreters/test-interpreter` with updated spec\n- **THEN** the server SHALL update the resource and return HTTP 200 with the updated object\n\n#### Scenario: Delete CodeInterpreter\n- **GIVEN** an existing CodeInterpreter named `test-interpreter`\n- **WHEN** a DELETE request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/codeinterpreters/test-interpreter`\n- **THEN** the server SHALL delete the resource and return HTTP 200 with the deleted object\n\n#### Scenario: Watch CodeInterpreters\n- **GIVEN** the server supports streaming endpoints\n- **WHEN** a GET request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/codeinterpreters?watch=true`\n- **THEN** the server SHALL establish a streaming connection and emit ADDED/MODIFIED/DELETED events as resources change\n\n---\n\n### Requirement: Resource Status Endpoints\n\nThe system SHALL expose endpoints for retrieving and updating resource status.\n\n#### Scenario: Get AgentRuntime status\n- **GIVEN** an AgentRuntime named `test-runtime` exists with status information\n- **WHEN** a GET request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/agentruntimes/test-runtime/status`\n- **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 200 with only the status portion of the resource\n\n#### Scenario: Update AgentRuntime status\n- **GIVEN** an existing AgentRuntime named `test-runtime`\n- **WHEN** a PUT request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/agentruntimes/test-runtime/status` with new status\n- **THEN** the server SHALL update only the status subresource and return HTTP 200\n\n#### Scenario: Get CodeInterpreter status\n- **GIVEN** a CodeInterpreter named `test-interpreter` exists with status information\n- **WHEN** a GET request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/codeinterpreters/test-interpreter/status`\n- **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 200 with only the status portion of the resource\n\n---\n\n### Requirement: Kubernetes Client Integration\n\nThe system SHALL integrate with the Kubernetes API using the generated client-go library.\n\n#### Scenario: Client initialization from in-cluster config\n- **GIVEN** the WorkloadManager is running inside a Kubernetes pod\n- **WHEN** the server initializes the Kubernetes client\n- **THEN** it SHALL use in-cluster configuration to connect to the Kubernetes API server\n\n#### Scenario: Client initialization from kubeconfig\n- **GIVEN** a valid kubeconfig file at `~/.kube/config` when running outside the cluster\n- **WHEN** the server initializes the Kubernetes client\n- **THEN** it SHALL use the kubeconfig to connect to the Kubernetes API server\n\n#### Scenario: Client uses typed clientset\n- **GIVEN** the Kubernetes client is initialized\n- **WHEN** the server handles AgentRuntime API requests\n- **THEN** it SHALL use the generated `clientset.Interface` from `github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/client-go`\n\n#### Scenario: Client handles authentication\n- **GIVEN** the service account has proper RBAC permissions\n- **WHEN** the server makes API requests\n- **THEN** the client SHALL authenticate using the service account token and certificate\n\n---\n\n### Requirement: Request Routing and Middleware\n\nThe system SHALL implement HTTP request routing with middleware support for cross-cutting concerns.\n\n#### Scenario: Route registration\n- **GIVEN** the server is being configured\n- **WHEN** handlers are registered with the router\n- **THEN** each route SHALL be mapped to the correct HTTP method and path pattern\n\n#### Scenario: Request logging middleware\n- **GIVEN** a request is received by the server\n- **WHEN** the request is processed\n- **THEN** the server SHALL log the request method, path, status code, and duration\n\n#### Scenario: Request ID middleware\n- **GIVEN** a request is received without an `X-Request-ID` header\n- **WHEN** the request is processed\n- **THEN** the server SHALL generate a unique request ID and include it in response headers\n\n#### Scenario: CORS middleware\n- **GIVEN** CORS is enabled in configuration\n- **WHEN** a cross-origin request is received\n- **THEN** the server SHALL respond with appropriate CORS headers\n\n#### Scenario: Panic recovery middleware\n- **GIVEN** a request handler panics during execution\n- **WHEN** the request is processed\n- **THEN** the server SHALL recover from the panic, log the error, and return HTTP 500 without crashing\n\n#### Scenario: Authentication middleware\n- **GIVEN** authentication is enabled in configuration\n- **WHEN** a request is received without valid credentials\n- **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 401 Unauthorized\n\n---\n\n### Requirement: Request/Response Serialization\n\nThe system SHALL properly serialize and deserialize JSON request and response bodies.\n\n#### Scenario: JSON request deserialization\n- **GIVEN** a POST request with `Content-Type: application/json`\n- **WHEN** the server receives the request body\n- **THEN** it SHALL deserialize the JSON into the appropriate Go struct\n\n#### Scenario: JSON response serialization\n- **GIVEN** a handler returns a Go struct\n- **WHEN** the server sends the response\n- **THEN** it SHALL serialize the struct to JSON with `Content-Type: application/json`\n\n#### Scenario: JSON field naming convention\n- **GIVEN** API response structs use camelCase JSON tags\n- **WHEN** responses are serialized\n- **THEN** field names SHALL follow camelCase convention (e.g., `createdAt`, `resourceVersion`)\n\n#### Scenario: Error response format\n- **GIVEN** an error occurs during request processing\n- **WHEN** the server returns an error response\n- **THEN** it SHALL return a JSON object with `error` and `message` fields (e.g., `{\"error\": \"NotFound\", \"message\": \"resource not found\"}`)\n\n---\n\n### Requirement: Query Parameter Support\n\nThe system SHALL support standard Kubernetes-style query parameters for list operations.\n\n#### Scenario: Label selector filtering\n- **GIVEN** resources with various labels exist\n- **WHEN** a GET request is made with `?labelSelector=app=myapp`\n- **THEN** the server SHALL return only resources matching the label selector\n\n#### Scenario: Field selector filtering\n- **GIVEN** resources with various field values exist\n- **WHEN** a GET request is made with `?fieldSelector=spec.image=myimage`\n- **THEN** the server SHALL return only resources matching the field selector\n\n#### Scenario: Pagination with limit and continue\n- **GIVEN** more than 100 resources exist\n- **WHEN** a GET request is made with `?limit=10`\n- **THEN** the server SHALL return at most 10 items and include a `continue` token for pagination\n\n#### Scenario: Watch with resource version\n- **GIVEN** resources exist at resource version `12345`\n- **WHEN** a GET request is made with `?watch=true&resourceVersion=12345`\n- **THEN** the server SHALL start the watch from that resource version\n\n---\n\n### Requirement: Metrics and Observability\n\nThe system SHALL expose Prometheus metrics for monitoring HTTP server performance.\n\n#### Scenario: HTTP request metrics\n- **GIVEN** the server is handling requests\n- **WHEN** metrics endpoint `/metrics` is scraped\n- **THEN** it SHALL expose `http_requests_total` counter with labels for method, path, and status\n\n#### Scenario: HTTP request duration metrics\n- **GIVEN** the server is handling requests\n- **WHEN** metrics endpoint `/metrics` is scraped\n- **THEN** it SHALL expose `http_request_duration_seconds` histogram with labels for method and path\n\n#### Scenario: Kubernetes client metrics\n- **GIVEN** the server is making Kubernetes API calls\n- **WHEN** metrics endpoint `/metrics` is scraped\n- **THEN** it SHALL expose `kubernetes_client_requests_total` counter for API operations\n\n#### Scenario: Resource operation metrics\n- **GIVEN** the server is processing AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter operations\n- **WHEN** metrics endpoint `/metrics` is scraped\n- **THEN** it SHALL expose counters for create/update/delete operations by resource type\n\n---\n\n### Requirement: Structured Logging\n\nThe system SHALL implement structured logging for all operations.\n\n#### Scenario: Request logging with fields\n- **GIVEN** a request is processed\n- **WHEN** the server logs the request\n- **THEN** it SHALL include structured fields: `method`, `path`, `status`, `duration`, `request_id`\n\n#### Scenario: Error logging with context\n- **GIVEN** an error occurs during API processing\n- **WHEN** the error is logged\n- **THEN** it SHALL include structured fields: `error`, `resource_type`, `resource_name`, `namespace`, `request_id`\n\n#### Scenario: Kubernetes API logging\n- **GIVEN** the server makes a Kubernetes API call\n- **WHEN** the operation is logged\n- **THEN** it SHALL include fields: `operation`, `resource`, `namespace`, `duration`, `error` (if any)\n\n#### Scenario: Configurable log level\n- **GIVEN** the `LOG_LEVEL` environment variable is set to `debug`\n- **WHEN** the server logs messages\n- **THEN** debug-level messages SHALL be output alongside info and error messages\n\n---\n\n### Requirement: Configuration Management\n\nThe system SHALL support configuration via environment variables and configuration files.\n\n#### Scenario: Server configuration from environment variables\n- **GIVEN** environment variables `WORKLOAD_MANAGER_HOST`, `WORKLOAD_MANAGER_PORT`, `WORKLOAD_MANAGER_TLS_CERT`, `WORKLOAD_MANAGER_TLS_KEY`\n- **WHEN** the configuration is loaded\n- **THEN** it SHALL populate the server configuration struct with these values\n\n#### Scenario: Kubernetes configuration from environment\n- **GIVEN** environment variables `KUBECONFIG` or in-cluster configuration\n- **WHEN** the Kubernetes client configuration is loaded\n- **THEN** it SHALL use the specified kubeconfig or in-cluster settings\n\n#### Scenario: Redis configuration from environment\n- **GIVEN** environment variables `REDIS_ADDR` and `REDIS_PASSWORD`\n- **WHEN** the Redis client configuration is loaded\n- **THEN** it SHALL populate the Redis connection configuration\n\n#### Scenario: Configuration validation\n- **GIVEN** an invalid configuration (e.g., invalid port number)\n- **WHEN** the configuration is loaded\n- **THEN** it SHALL return a validation error before starting the server\n\n---\n\n### Requirement: Error Handling\n\nThe system SHALL implement consistent error handling across all endpoints.\n\n#### Scenario: Kubernetes API errors mapped to HTTP status\n- **GIVEN** a Kubernetes API call returns `apierrors.IsNotFound`\n- **WHEN** the error is processed\n- **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 404\n\n#### Scenario: Kubernetes API conflict mapped to HTTP 409\n- **GIVEN** a Kubernetes API call returns `apierrors.IsConflict`\n- **WHEN** the error is processed\n- **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 409 Conflict\n\n#### Scenario: Kubernetes API unauthorized mapped to HTTP 403\n- **GIVEN** a Kubernetes API call returns `apierrors.IsForbidden`\n- **WHEN** the error is processed\n- **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 403 Forbidden\n\n#### Scenario: Internal server errors mapped to HTTP 500\n- **GIVEN** an unexpected internal error occurs\n- **WHEN** the error is processed\n- **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 500 with a generic error message (details logged but not exposed)\n\n#### Scenario: Validation errors mapped to HTTP 400\n- **GIVEN** a request fails validation\n- **WHEN** the error is processed\n- **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 400 Bad Request with validation error details\n\n---\n\n### Requirement: Server Command Line Interface\n\nThe system SHALL provide a CLI entry point for starting the WorkloadManager server.\n\n#### Scenario: Server starts with default configuration\n- **GIVEN** the `workloadmanager` binary is built\n- **WHEN** the operator runs `./bin/workloadmanager server`\n- **THEN** the server SHALL start with default configuration values\n\n#### Scenario: Server starts with flags\n- **GIVEN** command-line flags `--host=0.0.0.0 --port=9090 --tls-cert=/cert.pem --tls-key=/key.pem`\n- **WHEN** the operator runs `./bin/workloadmanager server` with these flags\n- **THEN** the server SHALL start with the specified configuration\n\n#### Scenario: Server shows help\n- **GIVEN** the operator wants to see available options\n- **WHEN** the operator runs `./bin/workloadmanager server --help`\n- **THEN** it SHALL display help text with all available flags and their descriptions\n\n#### Scenario: Server respects signal handling\n- **GIVEN** the server is running\n- **WHEN** the process receives SIGTERM or SIGINT\n- **THEN** the server SHALL initiate graceful shutdown with a configurable timeout\n\n---\n\n## File Index\n\n| Path | Purpose |\n|------|---------|\n| `cmd/workload-manager/main.go` | Main entry point for the WorkloadManager binary |\n| `pkg/workloadmanager/server/server.go` | HTTP server bootstrap and lifecycle management |\n| `pkg/workloadmanager/server/config.go` | Server configuration structures and loading |\n| `pkg/workloadmanager/server/routes.go` | HTTP route definitions and handler registration |\n| `pkg/workloadmanager/server/middleware.go` | HTTP middleware implementations (logging, recovery, auth) |\n| `pkg/workloadmanager/handlers/health.go` | Health and readiness endpoint handlers |\n| `pkg/workloadmanager/handlers/agentruntime.go` | AgentRuntime CRUD endpoint handlers |\n| `pkg/workloadmanager/handlers/codeinterpreter.go` | CodeInterpreter CRUD endpoint handlers |\n| `pkg/workloadmanager/handlers/common.go` | Common handler utilities and response helpers |\n| `pkg/workloadmanager/client/kube.go` | Kubernetes client initialization and wrapper |\n| `pkg/workloadmanager/metrics/metrics.go` | Prometheus metrics definitions and recording |\n| `pkg/workloadmanager/logger/logger.go` | Structured logging configuration and helpers |\n\n---\n\n## Dependencies\n\n| Dependency | Version | Purpose |\n|------------|---------|---------|\n| `github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/client-go` | Local | Generated Kubernetes clientset |\n| `k8s.io/client-go` | `v0.34.1` | Kubernetes REST client |\n| `k8s.io/apimachinery` | `v0.34.1` | Kubernetes API machinery |\n| `github.com/gorilla/mux` or `net/http` | Latest | HTTP routing |\n| `github.com/prometheus/client_golang` | Latest | Prometheus metrics |\n| `github.com/sirupsen/logrus` or `slog` | Latest | Structured logging |\n| `github.com/rs/cors` | Latest | CORS middleware (optional) |\n\n---\n\n## API Endpoints Summary\n\n| Method | Path | Description |\n|--------|------|-------------|\n| GET | `/healthz` | Liveness probe |\n| GET | `/readyz` | Readiness probe |\n| GET | `/metrics` | Prometheus metrics |\n| GET | `/api/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/agentruntimes` | List AgentRuntimes |\n| POST | `/api/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/agentruntimes` | Create AgentRuntime |\n| GET | `/api/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/agentruntimes/{name}` | Get AgentRuntime |\n| PUT | `/api/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/agentruntimes/{name}` | Update AgentRuntime |\n| DELETE | `/api/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/agentruntimes/{name}` | Delete AgentRuntime |\n| GET | `/api/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/agentruntimes/{name}/status` | Get AgentRuntime status |\n| PUT | `/api/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/agentruntimes/{name}/status` | Update AgentRuntime status |\n| GET | `/api/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/codeinterpreters` | List CodeInterpreters |\n| POST | `/api/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/codeinterpreters` | Create CodeInterpreter |\n| GET | `/api/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/codeinterpreters/{name}` | Get CodeInterpreter |\n| PUT | `/api/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/codeinterpreters/{name}` | Update CodeInterpreter |\n| DELETE | `/api/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/codeinterpreters/{name}` | Delete CodeInterpreter |\n| GET | `/api/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/codeinterpreters/{name}/status` | Get CodeInterpreter status |\n| PUT | `/api/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/codeinterpreters/{name}/status` | Update CodeInterpreter status |\n\n---\n\n## Notes\n\n- The WorkloadManager HTTP service serves as the control plane API for the AgentCube system\n- All endpoints that modify resources SHALL use the Kubernetes API server for persistence\n- The service SHALL be stateless, with all state stored in Kubernetes resources and Redis\n- The API follows RESTful conventions similar to the Kubernetes API for consistency\n- WebSocket or Server-Sent Events (SSE) may be used for the watch endpoints\n- The service SHALL support both in-cluster and external Kubernetes cluster configurations\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/delta-spec.md","exists":true,"truncated":false},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/delta-spec.md","time":{"start":1775844368222,"end":1775844368281}}}}
